{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528772"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14330"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14330"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.03,0.13,0.23,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7025"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55307"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7025"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40834"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4258"},{"type":"tags","id":"4264"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30674"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55307"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a burn on his right forearm sustained at his workplace two hours ago. He reports his arm came into contact with machinery at 150\u00b0C. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. The burned area is approximately the size of the palmar surface of the patient\u0027s hand. It shows erythema and blistering, is moist, and very sensitive to touch.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the percentage and degree of burn of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["2% and first-degree burn","1% and third-degree burn","1% and first-degree burn","2% and second-degree burn","1% and second-degree burn"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003E1% and second-degree burn\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient has sustained a burn that is approximately the size of his palm, which according to the rule of nines, represents about 1% of the total body surface area (TBSA) in adults. The description of the burn - erythema, blistering, moisture, and sensitivity - is characteristic of a second-degree (partial thickness) burn.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2% and first-degree burn\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the rule of nines estimates that the entire anterior surface of the arm (not just the forearm) represents about 4.5% TBSA, the palm-sized area described would be closer to 1%. Additionally, first-degree burns typically do not present with blistering or moisture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1% and third-degree burn\u003C/strong\u003E is partially correct in terms of surface area but incorrect regarding depth. Third-degree burns are full-thickness burns that appear dry, leathery, and are often painless due to destruction of nerve endings. The description in this case is more consistent with a second-degree burn.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1% and first-degree burn\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the surface area estimation is correct, the burn characteristics described (blistering, moisture) are not consistent with a first-degree burn, which typically presents only with erythema and pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2% and second-degree burn\u003C/strong\u003E overestimates the surface area affected but correctly identifies the degree of the burn. A palm-sized area is closer to 1% TBSA rather than 2%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccurate assessment of burn depth and extent is crucial for appropriate management, including decisions about fluid resuscitation and need for specialist care. The rule of nines is a quick method for estimating burn size in adults, while the characteristics of the burned skin (appearance, moisture, sensitivity) help determine the depth of the burn.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The rule of nines estimates that an adult\u0027s palm (including fingers) covers approximately 1% of total body surface area.","Second-degree burns are characterized by erythema, blistering, moisture, and increased sensitivity.","Accurate assessment of burn depth and extent is crucial for appropriate management and fluid resuscitation."],"references":["Burns - Secondary Survery. In: Trauma Victoria [online]. Available at: https://trauma.reach.vic.gov.au/guidelines/burns/secondary-survey","Hahn B, Roh SA, Price C, Fu W, Dibello J, Berwald N, Greenstein J, Chacko J. Estimates of Total Burned Surface Area by Emergency Department Clinicians and Burn Specialists. Cureus. 2020 Jul 23;12(7):e9362. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7444963/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40834"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14330"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40834"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T15:00:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T15:00:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7025"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55307"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/